BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/Website-cover-images-new-2026-02-25T123801.254.png
CATEGORIES:Guided Walk,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260225T070844Z
DESCRIPTION:Experience Paper Gardens: Art\, Botany and Empire through a Deaf-led walkthrough that reimagines how we engage with botanical art.\n\nThis guided tour invites Deaf audiences to engage with the exhibition’s exploration of botanical illustrations created in India between the 17th and 19th centuries\, and the complex histories of colonialism\, labour\, and knowledge embedded within them. These works were not merely aesthetic studies of plants\, but part of a larger scientific project that documented native species for their potential medicinal and commercial value within imperial economies. \n\nLed by Akanksha Kamble from the MAP team \, the walkthrough offers an inclusive\, visual-first encounter with the exhibition\, opening up conversations around art and ecology.\n\nThis programme is in conjunction with the ongoing exhibition\, Paper Gardens: Art Botany and Empire.\n\n‘Paper Gardens’ marks the continuation of a sustained\, years-long collaboration between MAP and Impart — an online platform fostering greater public engagement with the art and cultural histories of South Asia.
DTEND:20260307T094500Z
DTSTART:20260307T090000Z
SUMMARY:Paper Gardens: Deaf-led
UID:1203@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/paper-gardens-deaf-led/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/Website-cover-images-new-2026-02-25T164516.272.png
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260225T111547Z
DESCRIPTION:Image credits: Sudha Palepu\nJoin us for a mellow\, beginner-friendly pigment-making session on extracting colours from botanical sources. This is an opportunity to slow down\, take a close look at colours in their natural form\, and witness them transform on paper! During this workshop\, participants will learn to extract inks and pigments from select botanical sources using simple techniques.\n\nThere will be demonstrations of these techniques\, followed by guided hands-on colour-making by everyone attending. Upon making the colours\, each participant will get to paint with the extracted inks and pigments on paper and take home their artworks at the end of the session.\n\nThis event is in conjunction with Paper Gardens: Art\, Botany\, and Empire.\n\n‘Paper Gardens’ marks the continuation of a sustained\, years-long collaboration between MAP and Impart — an online platform fostering greater public engagement with the art and cultural histories of South Asia.
DTEND:20260308T080000Z
DTSTART:20260308T043000Z
SUMMARY:Painting with Botanical Pigments
UID:1204@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/painting-with-botanical-pigments/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/Website-cover-images-new-2026-02-25T163131.191.png
CATEGORIES:Talks,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260225T110144Z
DESCRIPTION:Image credits: The exterior façade of the University of Mumbai's Convocation Hall\, framed by it's historic Gothic architecture. Courtesy Somaya Sampat (2015)\nJoin us for a moderated panel on the documentation\, study\, and stewardship of built environments. \n\nArchitects\, conservationists\, and researchers frequently encounter layered histories — not only within buildings and cities\, but also within the materials\, skills\, and artisanal knowledge that shape them. This discussion examines how conservation\, adaptive reuse\, and heritage documentation inform professional intervention and public experiences. It also reflects on the influence of institutional frameworks such as UNESCO\, the Archaeological Survey of India\, and other heritage bodies on research methodologies and design approaches.\n\nBy situating built heritage at the intersection of history\, knowledge systems\, governance\, and contemporary design practice\, the conversation invites a deeper engagement with how historic environments are interpreted and reimagined today.\n\nThis conversation has been organised by Impart — an online platform fostering greater public engagement with the art and cultural histories of South Asia.\n
DTEND:20260308T070000Z
DTSTART:20260308T050000Z
SUMMARY:Evolving Practices in Architectural Heritage: Study\, Making\, and Meaning
UID:1200@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/evolving-practices-in-architectural-heritage-study-making-and-meaning/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/Website-cover-images-new-2026-02-25T123857.094.png
CATEGORIES:Guided Walk,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260225T070923Z
DESCRIPTION:Experience the exhibition through the eyes of a botanical artist.\n\nLed by Bangalore-based\, self-taught artist Nirupa Rao\, this walkthrough explores plants not as isolated specimens\, but as dynamic\, living beings embedded within rich ecological worlds. From strangler figs to basket ferns\, Rao’s illustrations in the exhibition reveal trees as thriving micro-ecosystems — alive with birds\, insects\, and other forms of life that shape their survival.\n\nThis programme is in conjunction with the ongoing exhibition\, Paper Gardens: Art Botany and Empire.\n\n‘Paper Gardens’ marks the continuation of a sustained\, years-long collaboration between MAP and Impart — an online platform fostering greater public engagement with the art and cultural histories of South Asia.
DTEND:20260307T070000Z
DTSTART:20260307T060000Z
SUMMARY:See like an Artist: Paper Gardens
UID:1202@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/see-like-an-artist-paper-gardens/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/Website-Image-1440-x-810-1.png
CATEGORIES:Performances,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260224T150703Z
DESCRIPTION:Step into a space where voices that were long silenced\, now echo with unapologetic power. The Reserved Compartment presents India's first Dalit-Ambedkarite anti-caste English Poetry Showcase—a bold\, community-driven revolution redefining mainstream culture through raw\, resonant verses and intimate storytelling. Curated for hearts ready to listen and minds eager to shift\, this evening at MAP promises to dismantle barriers and ignite conversations that linger long after the lights dim. Join us in honouring resilience\, nurturing love\, reclaiming narratives\, and co-creating a more inclusive tomorrow.
DTEND:20260228T140000Z
DTSTART:20260228T123000Z
SUMMARY:The Reserved Compartment: An Anti-Caste Love Poetry Showcase
UID:1185@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/the-reserved-compartment-an-anti-caste-love-poetry-showcase/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/Website-cover-images-new-2026-02-24T163505.324.png
CATEGORIES:Guided Walk,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260225T102757Z
DESCRIPTION:Image credits: Shruti Tharayil\nJoin Shruti Tharayil for a guided foraging walk and uncover the edible ecosystems hidden within our urban landscapes.\n\nCurated by Forgotten Greens\, Wild Food Walks are immersive community experiences that invite participants to reconnect with wild\, edible plants growing all around us. The session also introduces 'Map the Wild'. This light strategy board game is set in a climate-altered city\, where players navigate survival using wild edible and medicinal plants\, and discover how traditional ecological knowledge can shape more resilient futures.\n\nThis programme is in conjunction with the  exhibition\, Paper Gardens: Art Botany and Empire.
DTEND:20260307T053000Z
DTSTART:20260307T033000Z
SUMMARY:Wild Food Foraging Walk
UID:1197@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/wild-food-foraging-walks/
END:VEVENT
