BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/Website-cover-images-new-2026-02-19T154114.499.png
CATEGORIES:Talks,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260223T034923Z
DESCRIPTION:Image Credits: Mallikarjun Katakol \nJoin us as we delve into the experiences of photographer Mallikarjun Katakol\, who will be in conversation with Suresh Jayaram\, Founder of 1.Shanthiroad Collective. The conversation invites us to join Katakol as he takes us through his journey as a photographer.\nFor over thirty years\, his creative spirit and problem-solving ability have helped create compelling images. His experience in graphic design and advertising before becoming a photographer exposed him to the advantages and challenges of different channels. His practice sheds light on his unique approaches to framing and lighting as he works with a variety of themes.\nThis event is in collaboration with Ananya Drishya.
DTEND:20260226T133000Z
DTSTART:20260226T123000Z
SUMMARY:Ways of Seeing
UID:1187@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/the-ways-of-seeing/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/Website-cover-images-new-2026-02-25T142634.484.png
CATEGORIES:Guided Walk,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260225T085649Z
DESCRIPTION:Join us for a curator-led guided walk of the exhibition Paper Gardens: Art\, Botany\, and Empire.\n\nBetween the 17th and 20th centuries\, the Indian subcontinent was the site of extensive botanical surveys under colonial rule. Plant collection and classification were closely tied to imperial economic\, medical\, and political interests\, and botanical illustration played a central role in this project. Bringing together a new and historically significant collection of botanical art from this period\, the exhibition draws on recent scholarship to recover the often uncredited identities and histories of the Indian artists who made them.\n\nShrey Maurya\, curator of the exhibition and Research Director at Impart\, leads this guided walk through the layered histories embedded in these artworks\, and their relevance to how we understand the natural world today.\n\nFollowing the walkthrough\, writer and poet Sumana Roy will read from her essay in the accompanying Paper Gardens book. Drawing on memory and lived experience\, she reflects on the craze for the rhododendron and reconsiders the flower from within its native terrain.\n\n‘Paper Gardens’ marks the continuation of a sustained\, years-long collaboration between MAP and Impart — an online platform fostering greater public engagement with the art and cultural histories of South Asia.
DTEND:20260307T120000Z
DTSTART:20260307T103000Z
SUMMARY:See like a Curator: Paper Gardens
UID:1199@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/see-like-a-curator/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/Website-cover-images-new-2026-02-25T163230.802.png
CATEGORIES:Talks,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260225T110300Z
DESCRIPTION:Didymocarpus evalifolia\; Plate 1351\, Icones Plantarum Indiae Orientalis\, or Figures of Indian Plants\, Volume IV\; Author: Robert Wight\; Artist: Govindoo\; Lithographer: J. Dumphy\; Lithograph\; 1850. \nCourtesy Museum of Art &amp\; Photography (MAP)\, Bengaluru.\nDeveloped alongside the exhibition of the same name\, the Paper Gardens catalogue brings together over a hundred botanical illustrations from the 17th to the 20th centuries\, tracing encounters between plants\, artists\, and institutions across continents and styles. Featuring essays by art historian Dr Holly Shaffer\, botanist Dr Henry J. Noltie\, and writer Sumana Roy\, the book approaches botanical drawings as living documents.\n\nVarun Nayar\, Director of Impart and co-editor of the book\, will be in conversation with the book’s designer\, Tania Singh Khosla\, to discuss the possibilities and challenges of working with botanical illustrations in book form.\n\nReferencing her vast expertise with publication design — including past catalogues for MAP — Khosla will delve into the mechanics of working with such artworks\; discuss the narrative and aesthetic choices that informed her approach\; and reflect on how the book’s structure expands on the themes of the exhibition.\n\nThe exhibition\, ‘Paper Gardens’\, marks the continuation of a sustained\, years-long collaboration between MAP and Impart — an online platform fostering greater public engagement with the art and cultural histories of South Asia.
DTEND:20260308T120000Z
DTSTART:20260308T110000Z
SUMMARY:Botanicals and the Book: A Look Inside the Paper Gardens Catalogue
UID:1201@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/botanicals-and-the-book-a-look-inside-the-paper-gardens-catalogue/
END:VEVENT
